==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|so that}}, {{m|enm|so þat}}, {{m|enm|sa þat}}, {{m|enm|swo þat}}, {{m|enm|swa þat}}, from {{inh|en|ang|swā þæt}}, equivalent to {{af|en|so|that|nocat=1}}. Cognate with {{cog|stq|sodät}}, {{cog|fy|sadat}}, {{cog|nl|zodat}}, {{cog|de|sodaß}}, {{m|de|sodass}}.

===Conjunction===
{{en-con}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Indicates purpose}}; [[in order that]], with the result that.
#: {{ux|en|He must die '''so that''' others might live.}}
#* '''1900''', {{w|L. Frank Baum}}, {{w|The Wonderful Wizard of Oz}}
#*: He seized his axe, which he had made very sharp, and as the leader of the wolves came on the Tin Woodman swung his arm and chopped the wolf's head from its body, '''so that''' it immediately died.
# {{non-gloss definition|Indicates purpose}}; in such a way that, with the intent that.
#: {{ux|en|He tied a complex knot '''so that''' others would find it hard to undo.}}
#* {{RQ:RnhrtHpwd Bat|I|01}}
#*: The Bat—they called him the Bat.{{nb...}}. He'd never been in stir, the bulls had never mugged him, he didn't run with a mob, he played a lone hand, and fenced his stuff '''so that''' even the fence couldn't swear he knew his face.

====Usage notes====
* “So that” is used as a subordinate clause to show purpose or to give an explanation. It is used to show an action producing an intended result or a cause producing an effect. In the format ''Sentence 1 “so that” Sentence 2'', the first sentence is the action/cause and the second is the intended result/effect. In the format ''“So that” Sentence 1, Sentence 2'', the first subject-verb clause is the intended result/effect and the second is the action/cause.

